        <h1>About AppealAirportPCN.co.uk</h1>
        <p class="post-meta">Free Parking Appeal Resources for UK Drivers</p>

        <p>AppealAirportPCN.co.uk is a free, independent resource dedicated to helping UK drivers challenge unfair airport drop-off charges. We provide legally-grounded appeal templates, step-by-step guides, and expert advice to make the appeals process simple and effective.</p>

        <h2>Our Mission</h2>
        <p>Airport drop-off charges have become a common frustration for travelers across the UK. While these fees are intended to manage traffic flow at busy airports like Heathrow, Gatwick, Stansted, and Luton, many charges are issued without proper legal basis or clear signage compliance.</p>
        <p>Our mission is to empower drivers with the knowledge and tools they need to successfully appeal these charges. We believe that when parking operators follow the law and BPA Code of Practice, everyone benefits — drivers pay fair charges, and operators maintain credibility.</p>

        <h2>Why Airport Drop-Off Charges Are Often Unenforceable</h2>
        <p>Many airport parking charges fail under key pieces of UK legislation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Protection of Freedoms Act 2012 (POFA):</strong> Airport land is subject to statutory control and doesn't qualify as "relevant land" under POFA Schedule 4. This means operators cannot transfer liability to the registered keeper.</li>
          <li><strong>BPA Code of Practice:</strong> Operators must provide clear, prominent signage. Most airport drop-off zones fail this requirement, giving strong grounds for appeal.</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer Rights:</strong> Charges must be proportionate and reasonably communicated. Late-notified or excessive fees often breach these principles.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Key Fact:</strong> Airport operators lose a significant percentage of appeals at POPLA (the independent adjudicator) when these legal points are properly raised.
        </div>

        <h2>What We Offer</h2>
        <p>Our site provides comprehensive resources for appealing PCNs at all major London airports:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Free Appeal Templates:</strong> Copy-ready letters tailored to each airport's specific legal challenges.</li>
          <li><strong>Step-by-Step Guides:</strong> Clear instructions on how to submit appeals and escalate to POPLA if needed.</li>
          <li><strong>Legal Blog:</strong> In-depth articles explaining parking law, case studies, and recent developments.</li>
          <li><strong>Airport-Specific Advice:</strong> Detailed information for Heathrow, Gatwick, Stansted, and Luton appeals.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Success Stories</h2>
        <p>Thousands of drivers have used our templates to successfully appeal airport PCNs at the informal stage, avoiding the need for POPLA escalation. Our resources empower you to challenge unfair charges quickly and effectively, often resulting in charges being cancelled before any further action is required.</p>
        <p>Our resources have been used by drivers across the UK, helping them save hundreds of pounds in unfair charges while holding parking operators accountable.</p>

        <h2>How We're Funded</h2>
        <p>AppealAirportPCN.co.uk is completely free to use and operates independently. We rely on voluntary donations from satisfied users to cover hosting and maintenance costs. If our resources have helped you, consider supporting us through Ko-fi — every contribution helps keep this service available.</p>

        <h2>Legal Disclaimer</h2>
        <p>While we provide general guidance based on established UK parking law, we are not solicitors and cannot offer personalized legal advice. Appeal outcomes can vary based on individual circumstances. Always review the specific details of your case and consider consulting a legal professional if needed.</p>
        <p>Our templates are provided "as is" for informational purposes. Users are responsible for ensuring the content is appropriate for their situation.</p>

        <h2>Contact Us</h2>
        <p>Have questions about our resources or suggestions for improvement? <a href="/contact/">Get in touch</a>. We value user feedback and continuously update our guides based on new case law and operator practices.</p>

        <p><em>Last updated: April 2026</em></p>
      </article>
    </div>
